Despite the obvious advantages of the analytical interface traction force integration, the algorithm implementation into a specific DD-FE/BE code can bring a considerable overhead to a short research project. In such a case, using simpler analytical stress field expressions and standard Gaussian quadrature numerical integrations may be preferred. Figure~\ref{fig:NumErrorTimeContourAnaQmax20} shows how the computation error and cost of numerical integration varies with the number of Gauss points and the order of spherical harmonics expansion used in the stress field expressions. The numerical integration error is evaluated with respect to an analytical traction force integration using $q_{max} = 20$ for Ni with a dislocation--interface distance of 100~$b$. As can be seen Fig.~\ref{fig:NumErrorTimeContourAnaQmax20}, there are optimized combinations of integration point number and spherical harmonics expansion order to achieve a desired level of accuracy, and it is often more efficient to increase the order of spherical harmonics expansion than the number of Gauss integration points.

